Welcome to WPF and Stack Overflow. My solution uses tools/methods you may not be familiar with depending on how green you are, but they are very important parts of WPF so you should learn them if you don&#39;t already know them.

I would suggest that instead of using a `Canvas` with a bunch of manually placed rectangles, you use an [`ItemsControl`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.windows.controls.itemscontrol?view=netframework-4.8). An `ItemsControl` takes a list of objects and displays each one using a `DataTemplate`.

Take a look at the following code:
```
&lt;ItemsControl Width=&quot;500&quot; Height=&quot;500&quot;&gt;
    &lt;ItemsControl.ItemTemplate&gt;
        &lt;DataTemplate&gt;
            &lt;Border Height=&quot;50&quot; Width=&quot;50&quot; BorderThickness=&quot;5&quot; BorderBrush=&quot;Black&quot; ToolTip=&quot;{Binding SomeProperty}&quot;/&gt;
        &lt;/DataTemplate&gt;
    &lt;/ItemsControl.ItemTemplate&gt;
    &lt;ItemsControl.ItemsPanel&gt;
        &lt;ItemsPanelTemplate&gt;
            &lt;WrapPanel IsItemsHost=&quot;True&quot;/&gt;
        &lt;/ItemsPanelTemplate&gt;
    &lt;/ItemsControl.ItemsPanel&gt;
&lt;/ItemsControl&gt;
```

Each item in the above `ItemsControl` will be displayed as a `Border` control. All the `Border`s will be placed inside a `WrapPanel`. If you had 100 items, it would result in a grid pattern matching the image you provided. The [`DataContext`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.windows.frameworkelement.datacontext?view=netframework-4.8) of each `Border` will be the item it&#39;s representing, so any bindings will pull data from that item.

My solution would be to use an `ItemsControl` like the above, and populate it with the data from your &quot;data table&quot;, where each value from the table is one item in the `ItemsControl`. Then you could bind `Boder.ToolTip` back to the property of that item you want to display.

Let me know if you need any more clarification.

